text: Someone who changed my life? I'll give you multiple. The entire crew at Pixar, their movies have kept me going through multiple bouts of deep depression, & kept me focused on the goal I have of working with them. Finding Nemo taught me to just keep swimming, Monsters University taught me that my dream might work out in a much different way than I thought, Brave helped me to forgive my mom despite being exact opposites, & Inside Out taught me that it's okay to be sad, mad, disgusted, afraid, and joyful. I'm sorry that some people think that Pixar had lost their touch before inside out came out, but to me, they will never lose their touch as long as I live. #gooddino

text: Gosh, I really hope this Pixar film has potential to be something special, just like A Bug's Life and Monsters Inc.! My question though, is how the hell they're going to sneak the Pizza Planet truck into this film! John Ratzenburger is easy, but the Pizza Planet truck is tough to sneak in each film, especially in an atmosphere like this! Despite that though, I really can't wait for this film, because it'll finally bring us one of the first biggest Pixar milestones in history! TWO PIXAR FILMS IN ONE YEAR, BABY! HELL YEAH! KEEP ON GOING, PIXAR! Inside Out was a masterpiece, but does this film have the potential to top it? I certainly hope so, but just remember, Pixar: Please continue to express the magical messages you've taught children and adults alike over the years, because each and every single Pixar film makes everyone feel like a kid again!

text: Why are you people saying Inside Out was good? There was nothing special about it. I almost fell asleep during the movie because the plot was so weak. It felt like they made a movie for a psychology class rather than a movie with imagination and wonder. Of course, Pixar is basically the only giant in animation in the US because Dreamworks just makes 2 hours of jokes and call it a movie. They make a whole movie out of minions because they want to follow trends of what works instead of just making good movies. Toys coming to life, rats cooking in parisian kitchens, a space romance, those are what sound magical. Inside Out kept moving back and forth from inside Riley's mind to the real world and the plot was all over the place. I love Pete Docter, but let's be honest, it's okay to say Pixar messed up when they don't make a good movie.

Squirrels. text: Wow... No words for how amazing this will be... (Okay, I actually do have some):  It's unbelievable how much animation has changed within twenty years. The details in this trailer are absolutely stunning, and at some points it actually felt like I was watching a movie shot in real life. Then there are those cartoonish looking characters that appeal to audiences of all ages, which is a good thing. Finally, the trailer itself was able to tell a story really without any dialogue. Most trailers we see today need a lot of dialogue to tell what the plot is gonna be for the movie, but this trailer didn't need it. It's a challenge to tell what a movie will be about within a two minute trailer that has minimal dialogue, but of course, Pixar can achieve doing that and even anything.

text: Bare in mind that even though this is all hypothetical to where this is a story if the asteroid/comet never hit earth, that single act could have changed and altered many things. Humans probably would have never existed as well as bananas, ect.  It was because of that supposed meteor/comet (or whatever took out the dinosaurs) that brought mass extinction upon the dinosaurs, as well as other plants and organisms, so that the small mammals would have less predators to worry about, thus could thrive and evolve into humans and other recognizable animals.  Another interesting fact is that modern humanoids and dinosaurs could not coexist for one reason; there was much more oxygen on the earth during the dinosaurs' reign. Humans wouldn't be able to breathe the thick O2 if they lived with dinos back before the Cretaceous-Paleogene extinction event and vice versa -- if Dinos lived with us today they wouldn't have enough oxygen to breathe for that's how they evolved to be so large. Humans evolved with the post extinction oxygen levels and most modern plants. Humans weren't always the omnivorous brutes we see today.  Why Pixar chose the whitest looking humanoid to play the homosapien-esque character is beyond me. Depends on what era it is and where they are geographically. Is this before or after the ice age? Is the story set in the Cretaceous/Paleogene era where the continents are still extremely close to each other? Or is it simply based in Africa? Humans just recently migrated out of Africa hundred thousand years ago, which is why there are different skin tones based on sun exposure. So it'd take a while for this little boys' and his people to have such lighter skin than their ancestors for this take place. At least several or more million years after those dinosaurs comically watched the meteor/comet pass by, humans were evolving, born, migrated to cooler climates and then we get the main story we see for any of this to make sense.  But I know... This is just a what if made for fun animated film for kids and a story about friendship. Looks good, I'm gonna see it. Just wanted to point this out if no one already did.

text: *This movie looks as if it is in the same universe as DreamWorks 'The Croods'.*  Visually, the main difference is that there are now dinosaurs. Also, 'The Good Dinosaur' seem to be more about the perspectives of the beasts, rather than homins. Speaking of the homin species, this movie seems to be without neanderthals, but just a single homosapien child.   *It is as if the end reveal for 'The Good Dinosaur' is that the boy is actually 'Guy' from 'The Croods'*... Which considering that they look so similar, but with a matter of age differences is not hard to believe... But they are different movies by separate rivalling companies, so that's very unlikely to be the twist.

text: I'm still kinda irked with this cartoony character design contrasting the gorgeous realistic landscapes. I felt that going with something slightly more realistic like how the land before time would have made the danger and the perils in the adventure even stronger. Every time I see those T. rex onscreen I have a hard time taking them seriously. But other than that looks interesting so far.   It doesn't seem to have any sort of complex story going on. Most of the focus is on the young Dino getting back to his herd befriending the little boy. Admittedly this isn't the first time these sort of stories have been done but I'm curious to know what else is it going to offer. The relationship between the Dino and his boy have to be strong enough to hold the entire film if that's what it's ultimately going to be about.

text: I like how many folks are getting uptight about "Hey, dinos and humans didn't co-exist, and it could never happen!" What if the mass-extinction event didn't occur?  Is it so impossible that mammals could have co-evolved along giant reptiles?  Maybe at a slower pace?  If the dinos are living in today's age, then human evolution WITH competition from them would be set back.. hence why they are only primitives "today" according to this alternative time-line.  Sure, it's highly improbable, but not impossible.  Especially for a kids' cartoon. I'm more bothered by Arlo looking like an inflatable pool-toy against the environment.  Honestly would have preferred the backgrounds to have been equally cartoony.  But, *art!*, and all that that implies...

text: While I did mention this on a different video about this trailer, it bears repeating here as well. And before I say my main point, the film does look gorgeous. The details on each of the dinosaurs, to the water effects, to the rock texture, it's technically beautiful. With that said, it looks like the biggest problem with this movie, is the main Dino itself. I myself am not against the idea of having a kid-like Dinosaur as the protagonist, but there needs to be some form of consistency. It just doesn't feel right having lush, detailed, realistic environments being inhabited by a googly-eyed squash and stretch machine like the main Dino. That's not to say that squash and stretch effects are bad, but it needs to fit in with the rest of the movie. Maybe I could look past it if it was just like a side character that comes in for about 2 scenes, but this is the main character! Not to mention the clashing styles of having realistic skin on this goofy character is very distracting. I'm not saying the film won't be good, because knowing Pixar, it'll have a polished script, excellent visuals, and a lasting effect on kids, but I can't help but point out something so distracting.

I love dinosaurs, I love all 4 jurassic park movies despite their faults but this takes it too far, unless you make some drastic changes to this movie I will not see it. text: Okay, I know 85% of the comments are thinking that the characters look *"too cartoony"* and they don't match with the environmental backgrounds at all. But has anyone thought why they had to design the characters that way? There are many reasons to come up with that solution and I thought deep into it. For me personally and its not the legitimate answer but, I believe its because Pixar's rendering for this animation has become so great....*it looks like live-action*. I mean seriously,  take out the dinosaurs and you got a movie on a live-action documentary on nature. Like they just went out with their cameras, and started filming landscapes and added CG dinosaurs into them. The *cartoony characters* are the only thing that's making me believe this is an animated movie. .....But man, it so beautiful. I'm diffidently watching this in theaters soon! ^_^

text: A long, long time ago the Earth was ruled by dinosaurs. They were big so not a lot of people went around hassling them Actually not people went around hassling them because there were no people yet Just the first, tiny mammals. Basically, life was good. Then something happened, a giant meteorite struck the Earth. Goodbye dinosaurs! What if the dinosaurs weren't all destroyed? What if the impact of that meteorite created a parallel  Where the dinosaurs continued to thrive, and evolve into Intelligent, Vicious, Agressive beings, just like us! And hey, what if they found a way back?  Sorry Pixar, but you are just recreating the Super Mario Bros Movie.

text: I'm sorry to say that I'm not all that impressed by what I've seen so far of this. As far as I can tell, storywise it looks like a rehash of the first Ice Age movie, only with dinosaurs replacing the mammoths and other mammals. The subarctic backdrop even looks almost the same! And even though these dinosaurs are supposed to be 65 million years removed from the Mesozoic ones we all know and love, they really don't look the part. They look like the old stock Mesozoic dinosaurs modeled in this ridiculously cartoonish style, which jars with their photo-realistic environment. I'll probably see it anyway when it comes out, but I don't expect much right now.

text: What if this wasn't in the past?  I think this will fit into the Pixar Theory as so;  It'll be placed between Bug's Life and Monster's University. After humans and animals start to return to Earth, Animals start to be the first to evolve from BnL's radiation, into dinosaur-type creatures(hence their cartoony look). The meteor is a second meteor that just so happened to miss Earth, letting the new dinosaur-like creatures and humans live together. However, after the animals evolved too much, and humans begin to become wiped out once more from the dinosaurs, they split off into primitive 'factions' or 'tribes', thus the caveman-ey look. After more time, the humans AND the dinosaurs will evolve from the BnL radiation, into monsters. That is why there are both Hairy and Lizard-like monsters, because of the Humans and Dinosaurs.  That's my theory, at least.

text: People are taking movies way too seriously now. "This movie is so inaccurate!" You know what else is inaccurate? Toys come to life when nobody's looking, fish can speak and understand English, an old man can manage to gather enough balloons to fly his entire house all the way to South America,  a rat can befriend a human and learn how to cook, our closets are portals that lead to the monster world, and our emotions are tiny people in our brain that control everything we do! You'll enjoy the movie a lot more if you learn not to nitpick every little thing. In fact, instead of wasting my time arguing over a children's movie, I will eagerly wait for the movie and hopefully enjoy it.

text: I loved this movie. I'm glad I gave it a chance. At first glance when I saw trailers for it on tv, the conflicting art styles turned me off. But upon finally viewing the movie a number of times, I've come to love the art choice and the movie itself even more. Because it fits the story. Arlo doesn't belong in the wild, he's meant to stand out. Whilst others find it too cartoony I find it brilliant.   The story I felt was simplistic, perhaps derivative and borrowed many elements from other films, but that is sometime I learned to look past, but all films do in some ways, but it worked. It didn't need to be complex. it didn't need to be original. cliche isn't a bad thing. the Story of Arlo overcoming his fears and surviving in the wild, and watching his growth right from the start and righ to the very end, and his bond with spot which was heartwarming and felt organic, and the way it's told visually more than verbally is great.   Also the subtle progression of Spots character from wild lonely "animal", back to a human boy, which starts when Arlo and Spot first make that connection due to a common loss and find comfort in each other because they are both alone in the wild, and just watching Spot slowly uncover his humanity and evolving at the end, by finally walking on two feet when he goes off with his new family was fantastic.   I know this movie isn't a masterpiece, but I think the hate it gets is ridiculously unwarranted. Considering the production problems, the movie still turned out to be good, and still had that pixar magic. Could it have been better? yes it could have. But I appreciate it for how it turned out.  And you can't convince me that the movie doesn't feel like pixar or doesn't have that pixar magic, because those moments with arlo and spot are, charming, heartwarming, bittersweet, joyful, heart wrenching, pure pixar magic. That river scene with the sticks was truly powerful, and it was done with almost no dialogue all visually. I get it, if you didn't like the movie, more power to you. But it is FAR from bad which is what some people say and I just can't agree with that.

text: People love the bad before time but hate this Pixar movie I don’t get the world we live in even people say it rips off the land before time sure they’re are similarities but they’re both different the dinosaurs in the land before time don’t do agriculture or have domesticated species which would of helped them survive in the great valley during harder times but here the dinosaurs are practically sentient and have found way of coexistence without carnivorous dinosaurs killing the herbivores and herbivores actually began to eat crops instead of leaves bark or ferns its pretty genius if you ask me another thing  I hated Jurassic world because it had the same plot as the first Jurassic park but way worse I thought it was good when I first saw it but as I rewatched it and watched reviews of the film I realized this wasn’t a Jurassic park fan film like hoopsanddinoman said it was but rather a cash grab sequel that film made Jurassic park III look like a masterpiece heck it’s sequel fallen kingdom was a lot better   The good dinosaur is severely underrated and it’s not deserved heck even some people say this film destroyed Pixar’s reputation as a animation studio and that’s completely undeserved the good dinosaur actually had heart in it sure they added cliched dinosaurs like apatosaurus Tyrannosaurus rex but they added dinosaurs and pterosaurs that are underrated styracosaurus nyactosaurus heck originally they were going to add ankylosaurus triceratops and parasaurolophus into this film but I’m glad they didn’t because they’re too popular dinosaurs if you catch my drift it’s okay but not terrible or bad or mediocre   Plus what did people expect for the dinosaurs to look cartoony they made them cartoony to make them feel human so we could emote with them more heck Disney’s dinosaur in 2000 made them have human like faces so we could emote to them more I’m sorry if you guys thought I was ranting I’m just upset of how many people hate this film made by pixar

text: That beautiful animation. When I first saw the opening shot I genuinely thought it was a real footage. But it's not. I'll always be able to tell it's not real because its so beautiful it's better than real life. In fact the quality is so good that it's better than any camera can get. Modern cameras, doesn't matter if they use film or digital, just can't capture light and colour like that. They're nothing compared to what human eyes can see. This movie is closer to what I can see compared to any movie or photo I've seen. You simply can't build a camera with that level of quality, you can only animate it!
